Scott: There's only one person to play against.

124
00:05:34,230 --> 00:05:34,793
Scott: The game ended.

125
00:05:34,853 --> 00:05:35,778
Scott: It's like, "Okay, play someone

126
00:05:35,838 --> 00:05:35,938
Scott: new.".

127
00:05:36,441 --> 00:05:39,077
Scott: The same person you just played is the only person playing Dr.

128
00:05:39,117 --> 00:05:39,660
Scott: Mario Wii.

129
00:05:40,681 --> 00:05:49,020
Rym: So, I love Nidhogg, but I want to very briefly go over, now that I've played it a lot, and I understand how it works really well, it has some problems.

130
00:05:49,681 --> 00:05:52,020
Rym: And it's kind of worrying that it has these problems.

131
00:05:52,160 --> 00:05:58,860
Scott: Alright, so the person who's played it many more hours, do you see problems besides the problems that we, at, like, first glance, possible problems?

132
00:05:59,162 --> 00:06:00,388
Rym: Uh, basically, no.

133
00:06:00,429 --> 00:06:02,520
Rym: Well, there's two problems, fundamentally.

134
00:06:02,940 --> 00:06:09,680
Rym: Problem number one, you need to be able to auto-kill yourself to start in front of the other player.

135
00:06:10,001 --> 00:06:11,065
Rym: That has to be a button.

136
00:06:11,566 --> 00:06:15,260
Rym: Because running off the other side of the screen is not intuitive.

137
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:18,160
Rym: Now, it's fine if that is also an option.

138
00:06:18,180 --> 00:06:19,800
Scott: Not killing yourself is also not intuitive.

139
00:06:19,881 --> 00:06:20,620
Scott: Well, not killing yourself.

140
00:06:20,640 --> 00:06:22,818
Scott: It should be a respawn button, not a suicide button.

141
00:06:23,120 --> 00:06:32,059
Rym: What the button should do is, when you hit the button, it should make you disappear, as though you had died, and it respawns you at whatever its respawn logic is.

142
00:06:32,360 --> 00:06:34,498
Scott: Well, they should show you the respawn timer, too.

143
00:06:35,140 --> 00:06:38,600
Scott: Or whatever, you know, like, they should show you the spot and the time.

144
00:06:38,680 --> 00:06:42,200
Rym: Okay, so one thing, so if we're getting into all one, I'll just put, I'll frame it this way.

145
00:06:42,440 --> 00:06:43,465
Rym: Here's what I would change.

146
00:06:44,067 --> 00:06:54,520
Rym: I would say that you can hit a button at any time to respawn, but as soon as you hit that button, it starts counting down the default respawn timer as though you had been killed.

147
00:06:55,060 --> 00:06:59,917
Rym: And then, at that time, you always spawn in front of your opponent.

148
00:07:00,519 --> 00:07:00,940
Rym: Immediately.

149
00:07:02,321 --> 00:07:06,900
Rym: And if you hit the button to respawn again, then the respawn timer starts counting down again.

150
00:07:08,041 --> 00:07:13,977
Rym: I would add a variant, where instead of a respawn timer, you have five respawns, let's say.

151
00:07:14,419 --> 00:07:14,900
Rym: Just five.

152
00:07:15,221 --> 00:07:17,025
Rym: And they slowly regenerate.

153
00:07:17,286 --> 00:07:23,260
Rym: You can respawn immediately if you want, but if you use all five, you gotta wait for at least one to regenerate.

154
00:07:23,580 --> 00:07:24,322
Scott: Right, because it's annoying.

155
00:07:24,362 --> 00:07:31,560
Scott: There are situations where someone will, basically, the strategy of losing your sword, running and jumping over the opponent, right?

156
00:07:31,880 --> 00:07:34,520
Scott: So the only way they can stop you is by hitting you with their sword.

157
00:07:34,580 --> 00:07:35,760
Rym: Which is pretty trivial to do.

158
00:07:35,820 --> 00:07:39,460
Scott: Right, which is, you can do it, but you basically have one chance, right?

159
00:07:39,741 --> 00:07:49,340
Scott: So it's like, you can do it if you know what you're doing, but you can't consistently doing it 100% of the time is an extremely small margin of error.

160
00:07:50,360 --> 00:07:56,020
Scott: And because they go so fast when they're just running without a sword at all, you lose a whole screen.

161
00:07:56,360 --> 00:08:03,520
Scott: Even if you're like, "Shit, I missed it, I didn't kill them," run off the screen to die, you will not respawn in time before they make it to the next screen.

162
00:08:03,920 --> 00:08:06,200
Scott: And you lose a whole screen in like a fraction of a second.

163
00:08:07,464 --> 00:08:09,120
Rym: Which is fine, I like severe consequences.

164
00:08:09,160 --> 00:08:15,900
Scott: Right, but it basically means the best strategy in the world is force your opponent to be perfect, and unless you're 100% perfect, I win.

165
00:08:16,220 --> 00:08:17,280
Scott: And the game's over in two seconds.

166
00:08:18,062 --> 00:08:21,539
Rym: But, both players have the same capacity to do these things.

167
00:08:21,800 --> 00:08:24,560
Scott: Right, but then that first kill makes fucking all the difference in the world.

168
00:08:24,680 --> 00:08:30,600
Rym: Yeah, except against skilled players, when I do run into them, you can't just jump over them.

169
00:08:30,660 --> 00:08:30,749
Rym: Sure.

170
00:08:31,041 --> 00:08:32,879
Rym: And other people can't just jump over me.

171
00:08:32,980 --> 00:08:37,860
Scott: I think the way to solve this would be to make the throwing sword travel much faster.

172
00:08:38,941 --> 00:08:47,340
Scott: Such that when you throw a sword, it doesn't have to go instant, like they can't even react to it, but it should go faster than a person who is running with no sword.

173
00:08:47,662 --> 00:08:47,838
Rym: It does!

174
00:08:48,982 --> 00:08:50,280
Scott: Nah, you sort of get away from it.

175
00:08:50,300 --> 00:08:51,259
Rym: No, it goes faster.

176
00:08:52,041 --> 00:08:52,899
Scott: It doesn't seem like it's me.

177
00:08:53,041 --> 00:08:54,559
Rym: It definitely goes faster.

178
00:08:55,842 --> 00:08:57,999
Rym: But the thing is, it doesn't matter, because I'll roll under it.

179
00:09:04,981 --> 00:09:05,400
Rym: That's true.

180
00:09:05,741 --> 00:09:12,300
Rym: When and how to respawn in front of your opponent, and make it clear when and where you will respawn and when you'll respawn.

181
00:09:12,500 --> 00:09:14,295
Rym: The time and everything all has to be open.

182
00:09:14,315 --> 00:09:14,940
Rym: It shouldn't be hidden.

183
00:09:15,480 --> 00:09:30,640
Rym: I shouldn't have to do the bullshit I'm doing lately, where I'll back up or move forward to make sure that when I kill a person, or when I die, like if I don't have a sword and I know I'm going to die, I'll make sure that it happens in such a way that is advantageous to me on the respawn, because I know where that shit is.

184
00:09:31,144 --> 00:09:32,219
Rym: And I hate that in games.

185
00:09:33,381 --> 00:09:43,100
Rym: But I do want to leave the option to run off the back of the screen, because a lot of times what I'll do is I'll run back like I'm going to run away, then I'll turn around and whip a sword at their back, and then run off the screen.

186
00:09:43,540 --> 00:09:45,079
Scott: If they're a whole screen away, how's that going to hit?

187
00:09:45,940 --> 00:09:50,613
Rym: So, I throw the sword, it's coming at them faster than they can run, then I respawn.

188
00:09:50,654 --> 00:09:52,599
Rym: on the other side of them, there's a sword flying.

189
00:09:52,980 --> 00:09:55,636
Scott: I've never been able to, by that time, they're already on the other screen.

190
00:09:55,716 --> 00:09:55,998
Scott: How is...

191
00:09:56,664 --> 00:09:58,160
Rym: I don't know, you're terrible at this game?

192
00:09:59,222 --> 00:10:04,040
Scott: If I run off the screen, 99% of the time the person makes the next screen before I can respawn.

193
00:10:04,280 --> 00:10:05,260
Rym: Yeah, that's just because you're kind of bad.

194
00:10:06,041 --> 00:10:08,399
Scott: I'm running off the screen as soon as I have to.

195
00:10:08,680 --> 00:10:11,400
Rym: Some of the screens are wider than others, you've got to take all this into account.

196
00:10:11,740 --> 00:10:30,740
Rym: But anyway, the other thing that bothers me, and it worries me that this game was the artisanal game that was in development for so long, yet it has these fundamental problems, the actual direct sword fighting, as in move forward, move back, move the things up and down, at least with the controllers we have available on PCs, are actually kind of fucking fiddly.

197
00:10:31,325 --> 00:10:32,140
Scott: It is a little bit fiddly.

198
00:10:32,420 --> 00:10:45,880
Rym: And when I do find a very skilled player, you'll find that even to extremely skilled players, the odds of someone successfully disarming another person by anything other than random dumb fucking luck, pretty much zero.

199
00:10:47,180 --> 00:10:51,100
Rym: You don't elegantly in, out, in, out, sword, down, up, kill.

200
00:10:51,802 --> 00:10:53,600
Scott: The up and down is pretty good.

201
00:10:53,761 --> 00:10:54,359
Scott: No, it's not.

202
00:10:54,600 --> 00:10:59,160
Scott: But the left and right of just taking a step forward and a step backwards is a little fiddly.

203
00:10:59,260 --> 00:11:02,200
Scott: They need to make it easier to just be like step, step, step, lunge, right?

204
00:11:02,220 --> 00:11:04,073
Rym: They need to tighten up the controls, that's it.

205
00:11:04,094 --> 00:11:05,000
Rym: It's like Super Meat Boy.

206
00:11:05,220 --> 00:11:09,140
Rym: It needs Super Meat Boy level of control to be a real competitive game.

207
00:11:09,741 --> 00:11:16,380
Rym: As it is, it's a little fiddly, and I worry that they're not going to make it better.

208
00:11:16,920 --> 00:11:17,336
