00:33:03,830 --> 00:33:06,310
Rym: And we'd play games like Paper, Rock, Scissors.

642
00:33:06,490 --> 00:33:07,090
Rym: That's a good game.

643
00:33:07,610 --> 00:33:08,768
Rym: Or Run to That Tree.

644
00:33:09,250 --> 00:33:10,630
Scott: Whoever touches a tree first wins.

645
00:33:10,850 --> 00:33:10,992
Rym: Yep.

646
00:33:11,560 --> 00:33:12,189
Rym: Or loses.

647
00:33:12,530 --> 00:33:15,310
Rym: And then you're trying to drag someone else over to the tree and shove them into it.

648
00:33:15,795 --> 00:33:16,829
Rym: That was actually way more fun.

649
00:33:17,871 --> 00:33:22,470
Rym: So, a common thing we would do is add some stakes to any game like that.

650
00:33:22,790 --> 00:33:27,670
Rym: Whoever loses has to get the slick slap, is what they called it.

651
00:33:27,750 --> 00:33:29,746
Scott: You lick your fingers and on the wrist, pow.

652
00:33:30,510 --> 00:33:31,489
Rym: There's a technique to it.

653
00:33:31,770 --> 00:33:36,289
Rym: I've realized that young people, some kids get it and some kids don't.

654
00:33:36,690 --> 00:33:37,450
Scott: And that was another thing.

655
00:33:37,891 --> 00:33:41,810
Scott: If you won and you got the reward of being able to slap the person you have defeated.

656
00:33:41,990 --> 00:33:42,654
Scott: And you were good at it?

657
00:33:45,331 --> 00:33:47,289
Scott: But you're really bad at slapping the arm.

658
00:33:48,110 --> 00:33:50,368
Scott: Everyone's like, "Yeah, I let you win because what are you going to

659
00:33:50,408 --> 00:33:50,509
Scott: do?".

660
00:33:50,874 --> 00:33:51,302
Scott: "Oh, it didn't

661
00:33:51,363 --> 00:33:51,546
Scott: hurt.".

662
00:33:51,770 --> 00:33:55,164
Scott: And then if they win once, then when they do it to you, it's like,

663
00:33:55,345 --> 00:33:55,405
Scott: "Ah!".

664
00:33:59,133 --> 00:34:02,170
Rym: Well, you got to lick just the top bit of your fingers.

665
00:34:02,551 --> 00:34:06,350
Rym: And then you got to slap it just so perfectly right on the inside of the arm.

666
00:34:06,350 --> 00:34:08,228
Scott: You basically got to pretend your whole arm is a whip.

667
00:34:10,216 --> 00:34:13,250
Rym: You got to move your foot like you're a pitcher in a Major League Baseball game.

668
00:34:14,532 --> 00:34:16,529
Rym: So, did that add anything to our gaming?

669
00:34:17,730 --> 00:34:21,010
Scott: Well, I was thinking about this recently because I was watching some Korean television.

670
00:34:21,429 --> 00:34:23,748
Scott: In Korean television, they like to play all sorts of games.

671
00:34:24,909 --> 00:34:33,306
Scott: Various kinds of childhood or just casual games like, "Throw the paper at the paper to make it flip

672
00:34:33,487 --> 00:34:33,688
Scott: over."

673
00:34:33,931 --> 00:34:34,484
Scott: Or, "Roll the

674
00:34:34,585 --> 00:34:34,750
Scott: coin."

675
00:34:35,351 --> 00:34:38,128
Scott: Or, "Flick the ghost stone to knock the other ghost stone off the

676
00:34:38,168 --> 00:34:38,350
Scott: board.".

677
00:34:38,431 --> 00:34:39,230
Scott: That sort of thing, right?

678
00:34:39,351 --> 00:34:39,417
Scott: Yup.

679
00:34:39,891 --> 00:34:45,710
Scott: And a common thing they will do is add punishments for the loser or rewards for the winner or both.

680
00:34:45,969 --> 00:34:46,578
Rym: Like, "Eat a

681
00:34:46,659 --> 00:34:46,984
Rym: lemon.".

682
00:34:47,510 --> 00:34:52,590
Scott: Right, like, "Oh, whoever loses this game has to eat a lemon slice and can't spit it out.

683
00:34:52,650 --> 00:34:53,862
Scott: You just got to chew it and swallow the whole

684
00:34:53,904 --> 00:34:54,106
Scott: thing.".

685
00:34:55,174 --> 00:34:57,065
Scott: And so suddenly, it's like, "Oh, shit.

686
00:34:57,085 --> 00:34:57,468
Scott: This game

687
00:34:57,508 --> 00:34:57,850
Scott: matters.".

688
00:34:57,950 --> 00:35:00,969
Scott: And I was thinking when I was watching this, like, that's just a typical thing they do.

689
00:35:01,731 --> 00:35:02,235
Scott: Wait a minute.

690
00:35:02,256 --> 00:35:03,990
Scott: We play a lot of games with people, right?

691
00:35:04,131 --> 00:35:06,930
Scott: And often, you play games with people who don't care about winning.

692
00:35:07,050 --> 00:35:08,690
Scott: Because when you win, what does that mean?

693
00:35:08,832 --> 00:35:09,669
Scott: You can say you won.

694
00:35:10,030 --> 00:35:11,129
Scott: And if you lose, what does it mean?

695
00:35:11,430 --> 00:35:12,270
Scott: You can say you lost.

696
00:35:12,490 --> 00:35:14,630
Rym: Now, one could argue that that's an intrinsic reward.

697
00:35:15,572 --> 00:35:17,610
Scott: And also, I'm playing a lot of Netrunners lately.

698
00:35:17,950 --> 00:35:18,889
Scott: Not that I have, right?

699
00:35:18,970 --> 00:35:19,869
Scott: That's news to anyone.

700
00:35:20,250 --> 00:35:24,310
Scott: But at Netrunner tournaments, like, I only care about winning.

701
00:35:24,510 --> 00:35:25,587
Scott: Like, being able to say, "I

702
00:35:25,607 --> 00:35:25,769
Scott: won.".

703
00:35:26,651 --> 00:35:31,530
Scott: Other people there, like, care about winning because they want this swag that you get when you win.

704
00:35:31,630 --> 00:35:33,950
Scott: Like, I've given away most of the swag I've won.

705
00:35:34,090 --> 00:35:36,870
Scott: Like, I won a playmat at the recent tournament.

706
00:35:37,395 --> 00:35:38,290
Scott: It's an ugly playmat.

707
00:35:38,451 --> 00:35:41,130
Scott: I like my solid black playmat that I bought for eight bucks on Amazon.

708
00:35:41,270 --> 00:35:42,150
Scott: It has all these stains on it.

709
00:35:42,230 --> 00:35:44,049
Scott: More than I like that one because I don't like that art.

710
00:35:44,771 --> 00:35:46,324
Scott: And the guy, I was like, "Who's in second place?

711
00:35:46,364 --> 00:35:46,687
Scott: Here you go,

712
00:35:46,748 --> 00:35:46,949
Scott: bro.".

713
00:35:47,313 --> 00:35:48,648
Scott: And he's like, "Oh my god, thank

714
00:35:48,669 --> 00:35:48,750
Scott: you.".

715
00:35:48,810 --> 00:35:50,178
Scott: And I'm like, "It's a fucking playmat.

716
00:35:50,399 --> 00:35:51,947
Scott: It's like who gives a shit,

717
00:35:51,988 --> 00:35:52,169
Scott: dude?".

718
00:35:52,470 --> 00:35:52,692
Scott: Right?

719
00:35:53,035 --> 00:35:54,950
Scott: I could just buy them if I wanted it that badly.

720
00:35:56,371 --> 00:35:58,430
Scott: And these people are playing for the swag.

721
00:35:58,490 --> 00:35:59,790
Scott: There's a reward involved.

722
00:36:00,290 --> 00:36:02,670
Scott: And so I started thinking about, you know, we've done a show on gambling.

723
00:36:03,211 --> 00:36:08,070
Scott: But I think gambling is only a small subset of just stakes for games in general.

724
00:36:08,070 --> 00:36:10,070
Rym: And stakes in games are way more common than you think.

725
00:36:10,130 --> 00:36:10,770
Rym: Look at old Magic.

726
00:36:10,850 --> 00:36:15,430
Rym: I mean, Magic the Gathering had rules for putting up antis in the game.

727
00:36:16,050 --> 00:36:18,170
Rym: There were cards that affected the antis.

728
00:36:18,370 --> 00:36:27,370
Scott: In the original Magic the Gathering, the rule was supposed to be that you would, before playing a game, shuffle your deck randomly and pick out a card and put it to the side.

729
00:36:27,931 --> 00:36:29,890
Scott: And then play Magic with the remaining cards.

730
00:36:30,592 --> 00:36:33,570
Scott: So a card is randomly removed from your deck you can't play with, right?

731
00:36:33,891 --> 00:36:38,370
Scott: Then whoever wins takes both cards and is now the owner of both cards.

732
00:36:39,110 --> 00:36:41,989
Scott: And they even had cards in the game that said things like...

733
00:36:42,090 --> 00:36:43,310
Rym: Like there were cards that were protect.

734
00:36:43,870 --> 00:36:45,670
Rym: Like a bronze tablet could change.

735
00:36:45,910 --> 00:36:48,509
Rym: Like you could steal a fucking card from someone and keep it.

736
00:36:49,530 --> 00:36:50,069
Scott: There was that bird.

737
00:36:50,590 --> 00:36:51,349
Scott: I own your card.

738
00:36:51,670 --> 00:36:55,950
Rym: The jeweled bird was the card that you could swap in to protect a different card that went into the ante.

739
00:36:56,210 --> 00:36:57,449
Scott: Yeah, but now they have a jeweled bird.

740
00:36:57,810 --> 00:37:00,950
Rym: Yeah, which wasn't valuable until people started playing the game.

741
00:37:01,070 --> 00:37:02,990
Rym: And the jeweled bird was actually super rare and expensive.

742
00:37:03,050 --> 00:37:08,430
Scott: But anyway, it's like, you know, the game had stakes built in and they got rid of them, right?

743
00:37:08,711 --> 00:37:10,510
Scott: Because of the way it affected play.

744
00:37:11,691 --> 00:37:14,870
Scott: So it got me thinking about situations where you go to conventions.

745
00:37:15,130 --> 00:37:25,890
Scott: And there's a lot of incompatibility, especially in tabletop board gaming worlds, communities, between the people who care about winning and are competitive, like us, and the people who don't care about winning.

746
00:37:26,011 --> 00:37:27,690
Scott: Even in video games there's this conflict.

747
00:37:27,810 --> 00:37:30,390
Scott: And those kinds of people generally can't play with each other well.

748
00:37:30,732 --> 00:37:31,690
Scott: It's not a good experience.

749
00:37:31,690 --> 00:37:49,790
Scott: And I was like, if you added stakes, rewards and/or punishments, right, rewards for winners, punishments for losers of some kind, could you get the people who didn't care about winning to suddenly care about winning and change their behavior so that everyone could play together, right?

750
00:37:50,031 --> 00:38:03,870
Scott: Or could you use some reward or punishment to make the people who were competitive not care or at least get their behavior to change in such a way to get the games to go smoother when there were non-competitive players also playing?

751
00:38:04,871 --> 00:38:10,170
Rym: So, as I've put a lot of thought into this, I don't think it actually helps.

752
00:38:10,911 --> 00:38:27,550
Rym: I've read a lot of studies that show that in general if you give someone extrinsic rewards for a game or a task, like you'll win this ugly play mat if you win the tournament, people start playing for that goal and not for the intrinsic enjoyment of the game or winning itself.

753
00:38:27,893 --> 00:38:28,708
Rym: I have noticed that.

754
00:38:28,810 --> 00:38:35,170
Rym: Studies that show it can actually decrease your enjoyment and decrease your willingness to play the game when there is no longer an extrinsic reward.

755
00:38:36,274 --> 00:38:37,499
Scott: That is the thing that I've noticed.

756
00:38:37,539 --> 00:38:40,451
Scott: the most, right, is that I'll see people who will be like, "Hey,".

757
00:38:40,491 --> 00:38:41,907
Scott: I'll be like, "Hey, you go to the Netrunner on

758
00:38:41,967 --> 00:38:42,230
Scott: Sunday?".

759
00:38:42,230 --> 00:38:42,994
Scott: They'll be like, "Do they have

760
00:38:43,034 --> 00:38:43,476
Scott: prizes?".

761
00:38:43,797 --> 00:38:46,048
Scott: And I'm like, "Uh, I don't know, do

762
00:38:46,088 --> 00:38:46,249
Scott: they?".

763
00:38:46,470 --> 00:38:48,184
Scott: And they'll be like, "It's the same prize as last time?

764
00:38:48,204 --> 00:38:48,749
Scott: I don't want to

765
00:38:48,769 --> 00:38:48,870
Scott: go.".

766
00:38:49,390 --> 00:38:49,632
Scott: Right?

767
00:38:49,692 --> 00:38:55,610
Scott: It's like they're only going to the tournament because they might, because if they don't have the prize that they want, they're not going to go.

768
00:38:55,992 --> 00:39:01,521
Scott: Some other guy was seriously talking about going to Bulgaria because there was a Netrunner tournament with a 1,300 euro prize for the winner.

769
00:39:04,050 --> 00:39:04,976
Scott: It's like, "But you're not going to win.

770
00:39:04,997 --> 00:39:06,265
Scott: You're just going to go on a trip to Bulgaria.

771
00:39:06,286 --> 00:39:06,910
Scott: Are you crazy?

772
00:39:07,611 --> 00:39:08,154
Scott: What is wrong with

773
00:39:08,174 --> 00:39:08,315
Scott: you?".

774
00:39:08,335 --> 00:39:10,485
Scott: I mean, not that Bulgaria is not nice.

775
00:39:10,505 --> 00:39:11,490
Scott: I wouldn't want to just go there.

776
00:39:11,771 --> 00:39:14,429
Scott: But I'm not going there for a Netrunner tournament.

777
00:39:14,670 --> 00:39:21,910
Rym: But at the same time, our friend from the example in the beginning of the show is playing only for the extrinsic reward of the money.

778
00:39:23,010 --> 00:39:24,434
Rym: Or, is it more subtle?

779
00:39:25,617 --> 00:39:30,570
Rym: Are there people for whom extrinsic rewards do not affect them in that same way?

780
00:39:30,750 --> 00:39:33,610
Rym: I mean, I don't know much about these studies to be able to really speak to them.

781
00:39:34,153 --> 00:39:37,010
Scott: And is punishment different than the reward, right?

782
00:39:37,070 --> 00:39:42,328
Scott: What if we went to a Netrunner tournament and it's like, "Okay guys, whoever comes in last place has to eat a

783
00:39:42,368 --> 00:39:42,589
Scott: bug."

784
00:39:42,890 --> 00:39:44,209
Scott: Has to eat something nasty.

785
00:39:44,390 --> 00:39:44,774
Rym: All bug.

786
00:39:44,794 --> 00:39:46,590
Rym: We have this bowl of dead bugs that we found.

787
00:39:47,095 --> 00:39:48,210
Scott: Would you enter that tournament?

788
00:39:48,970 --> 00:39:50,229
Rym: Yeah, well there's an adventure time.

789
00:39:50,270 --> 00:39:51,397
Scott: Would you enter it in the first place?

790
00:39:51,417 --> 00:39:55,209
Scott: Because remember, the store wants to maximize entrance because they get an entry fee from everyone, right?

791
00:39:55,911 --> 00:40:02,190
Scott: Two, if you were in that tournament, how would you play differently than if you were just playing for no stakes at all?

792
00:40:02,911 --> 00:40:08,110
Rym: Oh my god, the last ante card in Magic was $19.95.

793
00:40:08,110 --> 00:40:08,768
Scott: Yeah, that's about right.

794
00:40:09,391 --> 00:40:10,278
Rym: Oh my god.

795
00:40:10,298 --> 00:40:11,305
Rym: I'm old.

796
00:40:14,451 --> 00:40:15,814
Rym: But I don't know.

797
00:40:15,874 --> 00:40:25,630
Rym: I think if I had to guess, being not a psychologist, these kinds of rewards are only effective, or punishments, if one, they're very low stakes.

798
00:40:26,430 --> 00:40:29,270
Rym: It has to be on the level of the lick and stick.

799
00:40:29,710 --> 00:40:30,675
Scott: Right, that's what I'm talking about.

800
00:40:30,736 --> 00:40:33,310
Scott: I was thinking, practically speaking, right?

801
00:40:33,630 --> 00:40:34,629
Rym: Or the slick and slap.

802
00:40:34,930 --> 00:40:39,010
Scott: Right, is that we play a lot of games, often with people who don't care about winning.

803
00:40:39,251 --> 00:40:45,530
Scott: And it's like, could I get them to up their game by having some, you know, inconsequential punishment?

804
00:40:45,730 --> 00:40:47,308
Scott: Something that everyone would agree to, right?

805
00:40:47,550 --> 00:40:53,590
Scott: Because if you have some ridiculous punishment, like, yeah, you get, you know, smacked on the butt, then it's like, no one's gonna agree to that.

806
00:40:53,810 --> 00:40:54,448
Rym: I would agree to that.

807
00:40:54,731 --> 00:40:56,790
Scott: Yeah, but some people will not agree to that.

808
00:40:56,930 --> 00:41:00,090
Scott: And if you actually tried to enforce it, they would not allow it, right?

809
00:41:00,210 --> 00:41:02,830
Scott: And you'd just be like, fuck no, and if you did it, then you would go to jail.

810
00:41:03,131 --> 00:41:12,610
Scott: But if I have a punishment like whoever loses has to take this really sour candy and grab a fistful of it and hold it in their mouth, right?

811
00:41:13,030 --> 00:41:17,990
Scott: For like 20 seconds, people might agree to do that, and if they lost, would actually do it.

812
00:41:18,210 --> 00:41:22,190
Rym: I've found that the best way I've gotten, because you don't come to board game nights anymore, because you're a netrunner.

813
00:41:22,190 --> 00:41:23,329
Scott: No, I don't have time for that shit anymore.

814
00:41:23,530 --> 00:41:26,190
Rym: Yeah, even though you're gonna miss out on some Hans and Jotonica and Ginkgopolis.

815
00:41:26,411 --> 00:41:28,250
Scott: I'll play them plenty when it's time.

816
00:41:28,570 --> 00:41:40,510
Rym: So, what I've found is that the best way to get someone motivated to play to win is to get them to play enough, even if they're not 100% playing to win, until they get close to victory or win a few times.

817
00:41:40,570 --> 00:41:41,508
Scott: So they get a taste of it.

818
00:41:41,750 --> 00:41:42,710
Rym: Yes, once they taste that blood.

819
00:41:43,990 --> 00:41:47,830
Scott: When they taste the intrinsic award, they don't need an extrinsic motivator.

820
00:41:48,091 --> 00:41:52,790
Scott: I mean, look at one of our- Because they realized how, like we have, how awesome it is to just win, baby.

821
00:41:53,091 --> 00:41:58,550
Rym: Yep, look at some of our friends, I won't name names, they might be embarrassed, one of whom is really good at Zendo.

822
00:41:59,330 --> 00:42:04,610
Rym: Once that person realized they were very good at Zendo, they suddenly tasted the blood in the water.

823
00:42:06,413 --> 00:42:08,470
Rym: And I've seen that happen with a lot of our friends.

824
00:42:08,950 --> 00:42:14,170
Rym: So I think that's a better way than stakes to get people to take games seriously.

825
00:42:14,190 --> 00:42:20,870
Scott: That's true in general, look how demotivated the people were playing against you at Nidhogg, simply because they felt they could not win.

826
00:42:21,450 --> 00:42:25,750
Scott: So they just didn't even try to win because they felt they couldn't, even though they may have wanted to originally.

827
00:42:25,850 --> 00:42:30,970
Rym: I got to the point that I'd start faking it, like I would let them kill me a bunch of times, I'd let them get all the way to the edge.

828
00:42:31,510 --> 00:42:35,210
Scott: They didn't have the willpower to keep trying and trying and trying, right?

829
00:42:35,470 --> 00:42:35,537
Rym: Yep.

830
00:42:36,212 --> 00:42:42,110
Scott: Whereas me, it took me over a year to win a Netrunner tournament, and I only won when no one really showed up.

831
00:42:42,390 --> 00:42:45,550
Scott: And the people who should have beat me got in a draw, so I got lucky.

832
00:42:46,170 --> 00:42:48,950
Rym: So I think stakes like that, especially these low stakes.

833
00:42:49,531 --> 00:42:54,190
Scott: But the point is, I'm willing to just keep, I know what winning other games is like, and I want to win just to win.

834
00:42:54,690 --> 00:43:00,110
Scott: So I keep playing no matter what, where other people would become demoralized after not winning in short order and quit.

835
00:43:00,632 --> 00:43:05,630
Scott: Or they would win immediately and just keep playing because now they feel like they can win.

836
00:43:06,230 --> 00:43:10,350
Rym: So it is not out of the realm to use Nidhogg as an example.

837
00:43:10,510 --> 00:43:20,250
Rym: Maybe when I play against new people, I should make it feel close, but let them win a couple of games against me first, and then pull out the claws.

838
00:43:20,711 --> 00:43:21,930
Scott: It's called hustling.

839
00:43:22,210 --> 00:43:23,415
Rym: Yeah, here's my problem.

840
00:43:23,757 --> 00:43:26,890
Rym: I've tried to actually hustle people in my life.

841
00:43:27,932 --> 00:43:29,539
Scott: You know what stands in the way of hustling?

842
00:43:30,062 --> 00:43:31,770
Scott: Two things, morals and pride.

843
00:43:32,330 --> 00:43:34,388
Rym: Yeah, one thing stands in that way, and that's pride.

844
00:43:35,110 --> 00:43:35,450
Scott: Pride only.

845
00:43:36,671 --> 00:43:42,285
Rym: I tried to legit hustle some people at poker.

846
00:43:42,406 --> 00:43:44,090
Rym: during that time we were trying to win that PS2.

847
00:43:46,012 --> 00:43:48,050
Scott: First of all, there was another guy there who was just winning.

848
00:43:48,230 --> 00:43:59,270
Rym: Yeah, well he hustled because he wormed his way into the game, lost a bunch, and then suddenly started winning every hand, and his friends used social pressure to keep other people in the game.

849
00:43:59,511 --> 00:44:00,683
Scott: What did we put all our money on?

850
00:44:00,703 --> 00:44:01,350
Scott: Was it red or black?

851
00:44:01,513 --> 00:44:02,170
Rym: I don't remember.

852
00:44:02,190 --> 00:44:03,039
Scott: We should have put it on the other one.

853
00:44:03,060 --> 00:44:03,828
Scott: We would have had that PS2.

854
00:44:04,271 --> 00:44:05,062
Rym: You know what we put it on?

855
00:44:05,326 --> 00:44:05,610
Rym: Wrong.

856
00:44:05,850 --> 00:44:06,981
Scott: That's right, we put it on wrong.

857
00:44:07,041 --> 00:44:07,930
Scott: We should have put it on right.

858
00:44:08,393 --> 00:44:09,129
Rym: Never been on wrong.

859
00:44:09,490 --> 00:44:09,872
Scott: That's right.

860
00:44:10,796 --> 00:44:11,922
Scott: There was a one out of two chance.

861
00:44:11,942 --> 00:44:13,289
Scott: we could have had a PS2 right away.

862
00:44:13,329 --> 00:44:13,570
Scott: We didn't.

863
00:44:14,031 --> 00:44:24,850
Rym: But those low stakes like that I think only work, or at least only are not detrimental, if they're associated with games that are simple or closer to the party genre.

864
00:44:25,430 --> 00:44:28,790
Rym: If you play spot it with the slap, that would probably be fine.

865
00:44:28,790 --> 00:44:29,863
Rym: That would go really well.

866
00:44:29,924 --> 00:44:30,410
Rym: I'd love that.

867
00:44:30,510 --> 00:44:31,390
Rym: People would be really into that.

868
00:44:31,431 --> 00:44:32,689
Scott: I think spot it would be better with a lemon.

869
00:44:33,110 --> 00:44:33,869
Rym: A lemon might be good.

870
00:44:33,970 --> 00:44:37,070
Scott: Anyone who ever left holding all the cards as to eat the lemon slice.

871
00:44:37,330 --> 00:44:37,420
Rym: Yep.

872
00:44:37,950 --> 00:44:39,681
Scott: Or drink a shot of lemon juice.

873
00:44:39,983 --> 00:44:40,587
Scott: Just 100% lemon juice.

874
00:44:42,113 --> 00:44:47,370
Rym: But partly that's because the intrinsic value of winning that game is not as important.

875
00:44:48,150 --> 00:44:52,829
Scott: Also, the other thing is that depending on what the punishment or reward is.

876
00:44:53,351 --> 00:44:54,970
Scott: If the reward is just, say, money.

877
00:44:55,812 --> 00:44:58,390
Scott: The winner enjoys the money, but no one else enjoys the reward.

878
00:44:58,830 --> 00:45:02,550
Scott: The eating lemon punishment is enjoyed by all.

879
00:45:04,232 --> 00:45:07,430
Scott: All players enjoy that, including the person eating the lemon.

880
00:45:07,490 --> 00:45:11,730
Scott: They simultaneously enjoy and hate the punishment.

881
00:45:12,110 --> 00:45:17,210
Rym: That's why the key is that the stakes have to be low enough to where getting the punishment.

882
00:45:17,250 --> 00:45:18,720
Scott: If it's a punishment, they have to be low.

883
00:45:18,780 --> 00:45:19,424
Scott: It's a reward.

884
00:45:19,465 --> 00:45:20,290
Scott: They can be any scale.

885
00:45:20,430 --> 00:45:23,609
Rym: Yes, but the punishment has to, well, if the reward is too high.

886
00:45:24,330 --> 00:45:25,310
Scott: People get too serious.

887
00:45:26,590 --> 00:45:30,250
Scott: It becomes serious business and people would be killing each other to get the million dollars.

888
00:45:30,570 --> 00:45:32,550
Rym: Which would be fine if it's a game like Puerto Rico.

889
00:45:32,630 --> 00:45:35,789
Rym: If I was playing Puerto Rico for a million dollars, that would be the best thing ever.

890
00:45:36,111 --> 00:45:39,130
Scott: Go look at Major League Gaming and stuff.

891
00:45:39,710 --> 00:45:42,090
Scott: The Dotads and such of the world.

892
00:45:42,832 --> 00:45:43,738
Scott: The Magic Tournaments.

893
00:45:43,758 --> 00:45:45,410
Scott: The kind of culture that exists there.

894
00:45:46,014 --> 00:45:47,430
Scott: Where the prizes are so large.

895
00:45:47,910 --> 00:45:52,650
Scott: That culture exists because the prizes are so large and those people need that money.

896
00:45:53,091 --> 00:45:55,690
Scott: They're banking on that money to live because they're pro players.

897
00:45:55,890 --> 00:45:57,009
Scott: Like pro poker, pro golf.

898
00:45:57,833 --> 00:45:59,370
Scott: You see that kind of culture will emerge.

899
00:45:59,470 --> 00:46:04,590
Scott: If the prizes are low, like in Netrunner, then you see a different culture.

900
00:46:04,831 --> 00:46:08,110
Scott: Even though there's still those people who are affected by the extrinsic award.

901
00:46:08,771 --> 00:46:11,781
Scott: The culture of, "I'm playing Netrunner for my life.

902
00:46:12,082 --> 00:46:13,327
Scott: I'm super serious about this.

903
00:46:13,407 --> 00:46:13,949
Scott: Fuck all you

904
00:46:13,989 --> 00:46:14,210
Scott: guys."

905
00:46:14,310 --> 00:46:14,954
Scott: Does not exist.

906
00:46:15,014 --> 00:46:16,924
Scott: Everyone's just like, "Hey, good job winning.

907
00:46:16,944 --> 00:46:17,467
Scott: Yeah, what's

908
00:46:17,588 --> 00:46:17,648
Scott: up?".

909
00:46:19,471 --> 00:46:24,570
Scott: Because they care about the prize, but don't care that much about the prize.

910
00:46:24,790 --> 00:46:26,430
Scott: Because it's not ridiculous.

911
00:46:26,450 --> 00:46:30,069
Rym: So the stake has to be kind of on the level of those jackass shows.

912
00:46:30,691 --> 00:46:32,529
Rym: Where you're all kind of in this together.

913
00:46:32,610 --> 00:46:34,470
Scott: The injury to the emergency room trip.

914
00:46:34,792 --> 00:46:36,970
Rym: But that's low stakes for that group of people.

915
00:46:37,310 --> 00:46:43,450
Rym: For the group that's playing, the stakes have to be low relative to the tolerances of everyone in that group.

916
00:46:44,450 --> 00:46:52,885
Scott: So if you have a group of ridiculous daredevils, the punishment could be like, "Oh, you gotta skydive up to

917
00:46:52,905 --> 00:46:53,247
Scott: whatever.".

918
00:46:53,710 --> 00:46:55,084
Scott: Because for them, it's like, "Okay,

919
00:46:55,104 --> 00:46:55,448
Scott: whatevs.".

920
00:46:56,673 --> 00:47:01,470
Rym: It has to be a punishment that the person getting punished will enjoy and laugh along with.

921
00:47:01,611 --> 00:47:03,049
Rym: Like that level or else it's no good.

922
00:47:03,490 --> 00:47:06,450
Rym: Otherwise you're just going to further demotivate the people.

923
00:47:06,670 --> 00:47:10,206
Scott: Even if I say, "Yes, I agree to play in this game and have this

924
00:47:10,267 --> 00:47:10,749
Scott: punishment."

925
00:47:11,171 --> 00:47:14,827
Scott: If at the end I lose and I say, "Actually, no, you're not doing that punishment to

926
00:47:14,887 --> 00:47:15,008
Scott: me."

927
00:47:15,731 --> 00:47:18,330
Scott: And then you do it, then I can call the police and that's a problem.

928
00:47:19,895 --> 00:47:21,570
Rym: What if we signed a contract ahead of time?

929
00:47:22,331 --> 00:47:23,649
Scott: I don't even know if that would fly.

930
00:47:23,850 --> 00:47:25,630
Rym: I think it would depend on the nature of the punishment.

931
00:47:25,950 --> 00:47:27,410
Scott: Obviously, obviously.

932
00:47:27,914 --> 00:47:28,429
Rym: Eat this bug.

933
00:47:28,791 --> 00:47:36,547
Scott: Yeah, if I signed a contract that said, "I will eat the bug," and then I refused to eat it, it's like, "Could you sue me for breach of

934
00:47:36,567 --> 00:47:37,010
Scott: contract?"

935
00:47:37,112 --> 00:47:37,549
Scott: Probably.

936
00:47:38,870 --> 00:47:40,743
Rym: I'm sure some lawyer will chime in and be like, "Well...".

937
00:47:42,011 --> 00:47:43,726
Scott: It's like, "You can't make me eat a fucking bug.

938
00:47:43,786 --> 00:47:44,069
Scott: Really?".

939
00:47:44,613 --> 00:47:46,550
Rym: Why would you sign a contract saying you'd eat a bug?

940
00:47:46,670 --> 00:47:50,390
Scott: Because I thought I would do it, but then I developed a bug phobia afterwards.

941
00:47:51,451 --> 00:47:55,250
Scott: When I was actually confronted with the situation, I realized I changed my mind.

942
00:47:55,411 --> 00:48:03,010
Rym: So, I'm going to read for you a card from Magic that did stuff with the ante to give everyone out there an idea of what this shit was like.

943
00:48:03,150 --> 00:48:04,440
Rym: It wasn't just, "Play for

944
00:48:04,481 --> 00:48:05,005
Rym: keepsies.".

945
00:48:05,630 --> 00:48:09,190
Rym: So, Temerian Fiends caused one colorless and two black.

946
00:48:09,330 --> 00:48:09,663
Rym: It's a creature.

947
00:48:09,684 --> 00:48:09,830
Rym: One, one.

948
00:48:09,830 --> 00:48:12,090
Scott: So you can just play that, like, fucking the third turn of the game.

949
00:48:12,210 --> 00:48:12,431
Scott: Yes.

950
00:48:12,692 --> 00:48:17,006
Rym: First text, "Remove Temerian Fiends from your deck if you're not playing for

951
00:48:17,087 --> 00:48:17,347
Rym: ante.".

952
00:48:18,272 --> 00:48:19,870
Scott: So you can only play it if you're playing for ante.

953
00:48:21,175 --> 00:48:29,344
Scott: Actually, that card is ridiculously strong because when you don't play for ante, your deck just legally got smaller by four copies.

954
00:48:31,550 --> 00:48:33,450
Scott: So now you have a 56-card deck instead of a 60-card deck.

955
00:48:33,450 --> 00:48:35,510
Rym: I don't know which rule would take precedence.

956
00:48:36,335 --> 00:48:36,568
Rym: Right?

957
00:48:36,991 --> 00:48:40,070
Rym: It might remove you below the limit and then you're just immediately disqualified.

958
00:48:40,692 --> 00:48:42,044
Scott: I think that's it.

959
00:48:42,084 --> 00:48:42,730
Scott: Anyway, continue.

960
00:48:43,610 --> 00:48:46,427
Rym: "Spend three black mana and sacrifice Temerian

961
00:48:46,467 --> 00:48:46,749
Rym: Fiends.".

962
00:48:47,011 --> 00:48:50,830
Scott: Well, you already have three black mana, most likely, because you used two colorless and a black to install it.

963
00:48:50,830 --> 00:48:51,450
Scott: Don't listen to this shit.

964
00:48:52,010 --> 00:48:52,295
Scott: Summon it.

965
00:48:52,316 --> 00:48:52,804
Scott: Summon it.

966
00:48:52,845 --> 00:48:53,150
Scott: Sorry.

967
00:48:53,450 --> 00:49:05,969
Rym: "The owner of target artifact may ante the top card of his or her library if the player does not exchange ownership of that artifact and Temerian

968
00:49:06,009 --> 00:49:06,270
Rym: Fiends.".

969
00:49:06,290 --> 00:49:09,829
Scott: So if someone has an artifact card, it's like, "Give me that

970
00:49:09,849 --> 00:49:10,070
Scott: artifact."

971
00:49:10,471 --> 00:49:10,787
Scott: To keep.

972
00:49:11,232 --> 00:49:13,909
Scott: Or, "Give me the top card of your deck and...".

973
00:49:14,151 --> 00:49:16,110
Rym: I'll give you the Temerian Fiends in return.

974
00:49:16,451 --> 00:49:16,773
Scott: Right.

975
00:49:16,813 --> 00:49:19,725
Scott: So basically it punishes anyone who plays an artifact.

976
00:49:19,745 --> 00:49:20,970
Scott: that's worth a lot of money.

977
00:49:21,150 --> 00:49:24,790
Scott: Oh, you're playing Alpha Magic, Black Lotus, Moxes, all artifacts.

978
00:49:26,773 --> 00:49:27,930
Rym: Yeah, ante was awesome.

979
00:49:28,351 --> 00:49:29,048
Scott: Yes, it was.

980
00:49:29,470 --> 00:49:30,320
Scott: "Give me that Black

981
00:49:30,361 --> 00:49:30,725
Scott: Lotus.".

982
00:49:31,497 --> 00:49:32,229
Scott: I don't want to.

983
00:49:32,330 --> 00:49:33,257
Scott: "Give me the top card of your

984
00:49:33,278 --> 00:49:33,519
Scott: deck.".

985
00:49:33,721 --> 00:49:34,487
Scott: Mox Emerald.

986
00:49:34,608 --> 00:49:34,790
Rym: Fuck.

987
00:49:36,152 --> 00:49:38,869
Scott: Oh, another Black Lotus, because you're allowed to have four, right?

988
00:49:39,911 --> 00:49:40,353
Rym: Uh, yeah.

989
00:49:40,413 --> 00:49:45,770
Rym: Though Black Lotus and Sol Ring and all those things were restricted to one pretty early on before they were banned.

990
00:49:46,036 --> 00:49:46,590
Scott: I have a Sol Ring.

991
00:49:47,390 --> 00:49:50,550
Rym: Oh, ante is strictly forbidden in DCI-sanctioned play currently.

992
00:49:50,750 --> 00:49:50,871
Rym: Yup.

993
00:49:51,214 --> 00:49:53,009
Scott: They banned it really early on.

994
00:49:53,390 --> 00:49:55,767
Rym: In unsanctioned games, we're not prohibited by law.

995
00:49:56,518 --> 00:49:56,645
Rym: Yup.

996
00:49:56,891 --> 00:49:57,407
Rym: That's boring.

997
00:49:57,910 --> 00:49:58,041
Scott: Yup.

998
00:49:59,551 --> 00:49:59,697
Scott: Yup.

999
00:50:00,970 --> 00:50:07,369
Scott: Maybe we could make a game, right, to where somehow to work the ante in, right, where it's like...

1000
00:50:07,652 --> 00:50:08,450
Rym: I see where you're going with this.

1001
00:50:08,450 --> 00:50:11,430
Scott: It's more like Dominion, but you play multiple games, right?

1002
00:50:11,630 --> 00:50:18,610
Scott: But you still ante the game cards from the game, and then you get them back, and then you have to play another game.

1003
00:50:18,650 --> 00:50:24,689
Scott: So you're not anteing for the thing you're going to keep, because at the end of the day, you're shuffling all the cards back in the box, because it's a board game, right, that comes in a box.

1004
00:50:24,990 --> 00:50:25,060
Scott: Yup.

1005
00:50:25,310 --> 00:50:30,850
Scott: But you're playing multiple times with the same cards that you drafted or something.

1006
00:50:30,990 --> 00:50:32,040
Rym: Here's two other ways to go.

1007
00:50:32,060 --> 00:50:32,989
Scott: I see where you're going with this.

1008
00:50:33,210 --> 00:50:40,870
Scott: And by winning, you're getting your deck at least... You're changing your deck at least by getting cards added, and then you have to play again before putting the game away.

1009
00:50:41,031 --> 00:50:42,809
Rym: I'm branching this in two directions now.

1010
00:50:43,250 --> 00:50:45,541
Rym: Direction A is kind of like Risk Legacy.

1011
00:50:45,942 --> 00:50:47,309
Rym: If you do certain things in the game...

1012
00:50:47,610 --> 00:50:48,189
Scott: Oh, Dominion Legacy?

1013
00:50:48,550 --> 00:50:51,470
Rym: You can steal a token from someone, like Safe Cracker.

1014
00:50:52,510 --> 00:50:54,480
Rym: So you get the Safe Cracker token.

1015
00:50:54,742 --> 00:50:56,370
Rym: It has some minor effect in the game.

1016
00:50:56,770 --> 00:51:02,330
Rym: You can accumulate them across games, but there's still metal tokens.

1017
00:51:03,311 --> 00:51:06,583
Rym: I guess you could cheat by buying copies of the game.

1018
00:51:06,924 --> 00:51:08,369
Rym: Each game has two of them.

1019
00:51:08,792 --> 00:51:10,220
Rym: So buy like ten copies of the game.

1020
00:51:10,260 --> 00:51:11,930
Rym: Well, that's great, because I made the game anyway.

1021
00:51:12,893 --> 00:51:15,150
Rym: The other way I would go, which is a little more subtle.

1022
00:51:15,670 --> 00:51:26,009
Rym: Make a game like Netrunner that comes in a big box that has maybe a deck for everyone, and you're supposed to play for Anti with all the people who bought in on that big box.

1023
00:51:27,351 --> 00:51:28,034
Rym: Something like that.

1024
00:51:28,054 --> 00:51:31,890
Rym: Maybe it has ten decks, and you play with these decks.

1025
00:51:32,070 --> 00:51:35,789
Rym: Like ten friends each have a deck, and you play from your set, and that's it.

1026
00:51:38,793 --> 00:51:42,890
Scott: The thing is, someone would just buy one box for themselves and just make an awesome deck.

1027
00:51:45,576 --> 00:51:45,890
Scott: I don't know.

1028
00:51:46,350 --> 00:51:48,990
Rym: That's why these are concept ideas.

1029
00:51:49,290 --> 00:51:50,235
Scott: This is why I play Netrunner.

1030
00:51:50,255 --> 00:51:51,823
Scott: It's perfect, right?

1031
00:51:52,105 --> 00:51:53,090
Scott: Everyone has every card.

1032
00:51:53,410 --> 00:51:54,810
Scott: Everyone can make any deck they want.

1033
00:51:55,010 --> 00:51:56,519
Rym: Nidhogg, everyone has every move.

1034
00:51:56,559 --> 00:51:58,370
Rym: You can just play whatever strategy you want to play.

1035
00:51:58,510 --> 00:52:03,010
Scott: It's good for the same reason, but it doesn't have the customizing, which is fun.

